## Slide 15 – FPM vs ITPM · the two PM roles at PMI 👤👤

**Layout suggestion:** Side-by-side comparison (2 columns).

**Key points:**

| Topic | **Functional PM (FPM)** | **IT PM (ITPM)** |
|---|---|---|
| Focus | Business outcomes & benefits | Technology delivery & execution |
| Accountability | Business case · benefits realization · stakeholder alignment | Tech scope · timeline · budget · quality |
| Reports to | Functional business sponsor | PMI Tech (e.g. Manager IT CX) |
| Key Artifacts | Business case · BRD · benefit tracker | Architecture · backlog · cutover plan |
| Why it matters | Owns the **WHY** & the **WHAT** | Owns the **HOW** |

- **Both roles agreed BEFORE Gate 3** (G3) in the ePPM stage-gate process
- **Example today:** Omnichannel 360 – **FPM: Maura Ríos** · **ITPM: Ivan Fuentes**

**Speaker notes:**
This is one of the most common confusions for newcomers. The FPM owns business outcomes; the ITPM owns delivery. They are **peers**, not boss/subordinate. PMI mandates the two roles be agreed at Gate 3 of every project. For Omnichannel 360 today, I'm the ITPM and Maura is the FPM – we co-own the project from different angles.

